        <section id="summary">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">01 · Executive summary</span>
          <h2>Orient is a shared meaning system for humans and machines.</h2>
          <p>It has two connected products:</p>
          <p><b>Orient for Humans</b> — a thinking and communication space where teams capture knowledge, ask questions, resolve answers, create frames, share understanding, and build organisational memory.</p>
          <p><b>Orient for Machines</b> — a machine-ready meaning layer that lets agents, assistants, workflows, copilots, and applications consume the organisation's resolved knowledge, context, frames, and memory.</p>
          <div class="st-line">Humans feed the graph. Machines act from it. Orient keeps both working from the same understanding.</div>
          <p>Orient enters the market at a moment when companies are deploying more AI tools, copilots, and agents — but those systems still lack the organisational meaning they need to act safely and usefully. They can generate, search, summarise, and automate, but they do not know:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>what the organisation currently believes;</li>
            <li>what evidence supports a claim;</li>
            <li>what is contested, decided, stale, or still open;</li>
            <li>what should not be claimed;</li>
            <li>what people understand;</li>
            <li>when an agent should stop, ask, or escalate.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Orient solves this by turning human work into a living meaning graph: claims, evidence, contradictions, answers, open probes, frames, decisions, topics, people, comprehension, memory, and safe-to-act context.</p>
          <p>The commercial model follows the product architecture: <b>Orient for Humans</b> is sold by seat; <b>Orient for Machines</b> is sold by dependency — platform fee, machine consumers, and meaning consumption. The expansion path: land in one strategic team → expand to multiple human teams → add machine access for agents and workflows → become the organisation's shared meaning layer.</p>
          <div class="st-line m">Position Orient as the meaning layer between human knowledge and machine action — not a collaboration tool, knowledge base, or RAG product.</div>
        </section>

        <!-- 2 -->
        <section id="market">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">02 · Market context</span>
          <h2>The next generation of systems will act on information.</h2>
          <p>The last generation of tools helped people store, search, organise, and produce information. The next generation will act on it. Companies are already adopting copilots, AI assistants, research agents, sales agents, support agents, workflow bots, coding agents, enterprise search agents, internal knowledge agents, and automation systems.</p>
          <p>But these systems face the same problem: <b>they can act before they understand.</b> Most rely on retrieval — they search files, pull chunks, and generate plausible answers. Organisations don't operate on chunks. They operate on meaning: what is true, supported, contested, decided, safe to say, and still unresolved.</p>
          <div class="st-line">Companies need a shared meaning layer that both people and machines can use. Orient is built for that need.</div>
        </section>

        <!-- 3 -->
