            <div class="row"><div class="a">A search tool</div><p class="b">retrieves information.</p></div>
            <div class="row"><div class="a">A RAG system</div><p class="b">gives machines chunks.</p></div>
            <div class="row"><div class="a">A collaboration tool</div><p class="b">helps people produce work.</p></div>
            <div class="row"><div class="a">An agent platform</div><p class="b">lets machines act.</p></div>
            <div class="row"><div class="a">Orient</div><p class="b">turns organisational knowledge into meaning humans can share and machines can use.</p></div>
          </div>
          <p class="st-tag">Primary category line</p>
          <div class="st-line">Orient is the shared meaning layer for people and AI.</div>
          <p class="st-tag">Sharper investor line</p>
          <p>Orient turns organisational knowledge into a living meaning graph — used by humans to think and communicate, and by machines to act with context, evidence, memory, and restraint.</p>
          <p class="st-tag">Simplest commercial line</p>
          <p><b>Humans feed the graph. Machines act from it.</b></p>
        </section>

        <!-- 4 -->
        <section id="architecture">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">04 · Product architecture as GTM advantage</span>
          <h2>Two connected expansion paths.</h2>
          <h3>Orient for Humans — the first adoption surface</h3>
          <p>Teams use Orient to capture knowledge, ask questions, resolve answers, create frames, share understanding, measure comprehension, and build organisational memory. This delivers immediate value even before machine access is deployed.</p>
          <h3>Orient for Machines — the expansion and infrastructure layer</h3>
          <p>Agents, assistants, workflows, copilots, and applications consume the meaning created by humans: current answers, trusted claims, evidence, contradictions, weak spots, open probes, frames, decisions, freshness, confidence, context, memory, and safe-to-act signals.</p>
          <div class="st-line">The human product creates the asset. The machine product monetises the asset as infrastructure.</div>
          <p>This compounds: every human action strengthens the graph; every machine dependency increases Orient's strategic importance; every reviewed machine contribution can improve the graph again.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- 5 -->
        <section id="icp">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">05 · Ideal customer profile</span>
          <h2>Where knowledge is complex, decisions are consequential, and communication must land.</h2>
          <p class="st-tag">Strong early customers</p>
          <ul>
            <li>AI-native, software, and product-led companies;</li>
            <li>consulting and advisory firms;</li>
            <li>research-heavy and deep tech organisations;</li>
            <li>enterprise sales organisations;</li>
            <li>high-growth leadership teams;</li>
            <li>companies deploying internal agents;</li>
            <li>organisations going through strategic change.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>They share three traits: they generate a lot of important knowledge; they struggle to turn it into shared understanding; and they are beginning to use AI systems that need better organisational context.</p>
          <p class="st-tag">Best early wedge</p>
          <p>Not "company-wide knowledge management" — too broad. The wedge is <b>a high-stakes thinking space around a strategic question</b>: AI strategy, product launch, market entry, board preparation, sales positioning, internal transformation, customer narrative, research synthesis, or agent deployment strategy.</p>
          <div class="st-line">Help the team move from scattered material to a trusted answer and a shared frame.</div>
        </section>

