        <!-- 8 -->
        <section id="land-expand">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">08 · Land-and-expand motion</span>
          <h2>Land one workspace, expand to teams, become infrastructure.</h2>
          <h3>Land</h3>
          <p>Start with one high-value workspace — AI strategy, product launch, board prep, sales positioning, market research, transformation. Frame the first sale around a specific outcome: resolve this question, prepare this narrative, align this launch, build this sales truth, turn this research into decisions.</p>
          <div class="st-line">The goal is not to sell "a platform." It's to sell a better way to think through important work.</div>
          <h3>Expand</h3>
          <p>Once the first workspace proves value, expand into more teams, spaces, frames, answers, viewers, and machine consumers. Triggers: the team creates multiple frames; another department consumes the work; agents need the resolved meaning; leadership wants recurring briefings; sales/support need approved claims; unresolved probes become active work queues.</p>
          <h3>Become infrastructure</h3>
          <p>Long term, Orient becomes the organisation's meaning layer — where the company holds current answers, decision memory, approved claims, unresolved probes, topic intelligence, comprehension state, frames and narratives, and machine-ready context.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- 9 -->
        <section id="sales">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">09 · Sales motion</span>
          <h2>Founder-led strategic selling.</h2>
          <p>First customers should be sold consultatively, not through self-serve. The right motion is high-context, founder-led, strategic, use-case-specific, workshop-oriented, fast to demonstrate, and priced as important infrastructure — not a cheap productivity app.</p>
          <div class="st-steps">
            <div class="st-step"><div class="si">01</div><div><h4>Diagnose a high-value question</h4><p>What's scattered across docs and meetings? What do people disagree about? What narrative must land? What do agents need before acting? Where are stale claims or weak assumptions causing risk?</p></div></div>
            <div class="st-step"><div class="si">02</div><div><h4>Create an Orient workspace</h4><p>Use their real material: documents, notes, decks, transcripts, research, links, prior decisions, open questions.</p></div></div>
            <div class="st-step"><div class="si">03</div><div><h4>Resolve and frame</h4><p>Show the current answer, supporting evidence, weak spots, contradictions, open probes, and a frame for communication.</p></div></div>
            <div class="st-step"><div class="si">04</div><div><h4>Demonstrate machine value</h4><p>Show how an agent could consume the resolved answer, approved claims, evidence, caveats, and safe-to-act context.</p></div></div>
            <div class="st-step"><div class="si">05</div><div><h4>Expand to a team plan</h4><p>Full users for thinkers and makers; free viewers for understanding spread; machine layer for agents and workflows.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <span class="st-tag">Sales assets needed</span>
          <ul>
            <li>one-page category explainer; demo workspace; product launch, board prep, sales positioning, and agent context demos;</li>
            <li>pricing calculator; investor-style deck; technical architecture note; security and data note.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

