            <div class="st-card"><h4>Consulting &amp; advisory firms</h4><p>They repeatedly turn messy knowledge into strategy, narratives, and decisions for clients. Orient improves the work and preserves project memory.</p><span class="st-tag m">Machine expansion</span><p>Research agents, client briefing agents, proposal agents, knowledge reuse.</p></div>
            <div class="st-card"><h4>Deep tech &amp; research-heavy orgs</h4><p>Complex evidence, uncertainty, technical claims, long decision cycles. Orient structures meaning and helps communicate it.</p><span class="st-tag m">Machine expansion</span><p>Research synthesis agents, evidence-checking agents, technical briefing agents.</p></div>
            <div class="st-card"><h4>Product-led scaleups</h4><p>Need product alignment, roadmap rationale, launch frames, sales enablement, customer clarity.</p><span class="st-tag m">Machine expansion</span><p>Product agents, sales agents, support agents, onboarding agents.</p></div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 14 -->
        <section id="distribution">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">14 · Distribution strategy</span>
          <h2>Direct, founder-led, and category-defining.</h2>
          <h3>Direct founder-led sales</h3>
          <p>The initial channel: the category is new, positioning is strategic, buyers need education, the product needs consultative selling, and early customers should shape it.</p>
          <h3>Warm network &amp; investor-led introductions</h3>
          <p>Use investor and advisor networks to reach founders, CEOs, chiefs of staff, product leaders, AI leaders, consulting partners, and board members.</p>
          <h3>Thought leadership</h3>
          <p>Publish around the category, not just the product: meaning before action; why RAG is not enough for agents; the boundary between answer and uncertainty; humans feed the graph; agents need safe-to-act signals; organisational memory with judgement; strategy as living infrastructure.</p>
          <h3>Demo-led content</h3>
          <p>Show a messy board prep becoming a resolved answer and deck; sales positioning becoming approved claims and agent context; research becoming open probes and a frame; an agent asking Orient what's safe to say; a support agent abstaining because sources conflict.</p>
          <h3>Partnerships</h3>
          <p>AI consultancies, agent builders, enterprise AI implementation firms, product strategy and board advisory firms, sales enablement and transformation consultancies. The pitch: <b>Orient gives your agents and client work a meaning layer.</b></p>
        </section>

        <!-- 15 -->
        <section id="competitive">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">15 · Competitive positioning</span>
          <h2>Not just another AI workspace.</h2>
          <div class="st-vs">
            <div class="row"><div class="a">Knowledge bases</div><p class="b">store information. Orient helps teams resolve, frame, measure, and remember meaning.</p></div>
            <div class="row"><div class="a">Enterprise search</div><p class="b">finds files. Orient returns current answers, evidence, contradictions, and open questions.</p></div>
            <div class="row"><div class="a">RAG platforms</div><p class="b">retrieve chunks. Orient gives machines resolved meaning, safe-to-act signals, and meaning integrity checks.</p></div>
            <div class="row"><div class="a">Collaboration tools</div><p class="b">help people produce work. Orient helps teams know whether work is true, supported, understood, and remembered.</p></div>
            <div class="row"><div class="a">Agent platforms</div><p class="b">let machines act. Orient gives those agents the meaning they need before acting.</p></div>
            <div class="row"><div class="a">Deck / doc generators</div><p class="b">make outputs. Orient makes the work trustworthy: supported, framed, measured, and connected to memory.</p></div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 16 -->
        <section id="proof">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">16 · Proof points to demonstrate</span>
          <h2>Proof in concrete workflows.</h2>
          <div class="st-cols">
            <div>
              <span class="st-tag h">Human proof points</span>
              <ul>
                <li>A messy knowledge set becomes a resolved answer.</li>
                <li>A resolved answer becomes a frame.</li>
                <li>A frame becomes a deck, article, podcast, or Q&amp;A space.</li>
                <li>The system shows weak spots and open probes.</li>
                <li>The work becomes part of memory.</li>
                <li>Viewers can consume and understand it.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div>
              <span class="st-tag m">Machine proof points</span>
              <ul class="m">
                <li>An agent receives a structured context object.</li>
                <li>An agent is told what not to claim.</li>
                <li>An agent can see evidence and contradictions.</li>
                <li>An agent can identify open probes.</li>
                <li>An agent output can be evaluated for meaning drift.</li>
                <li>The system can say "not safe to act."</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <span class="st-tag">Business proof points</span>
          <p>One team starts → another team consumes the output → viewers spread understanding → a second workspace is created → a machine use case is identified → the customer expands into a larger annual contract.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- 17 -->
        <section id="metrics">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">17 · Key metrics</span>
          <h2>Measure meaning creation and dependency, not only usage.</h2>
          <div class="st-cols">
            <div>
              <span class="st-tag h">Human product</span>
              <ul>
                <li>active full users; viewer reach;</li>
                <li>captured sources; resolved answers; open probes;</li>
                <li>frames created and consumed; comprehension checks;</li>
                <li>repeat workspace creation; cross-team sharing; time from capture to frame.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div>
              <span class="st-tag m">Machine product</span>
              <ul class="m">
                <li>context calls; machine consumers;</li>
                <li>safe-to-act / not-safe-to-act signals; abstention rate;</li>
                <li>evidence retrievals; agent output evaluations;</li>
                <li>unsupported claim reduction; meaning integrity pass rate; machine proposals reviewed.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <span class="st-tag">Commercial</span>
          <p>Average contract value; expansion from one to multiple workspaces; conversion from human-only to human + machine; machine consumers per account; ARR per full user; ARR per account; net revenue retention.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- 18 -->
        <section id="risks">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">18 · Risks &amp; mitigations</span>
          <h2>Known risks, with mitigations.</h2>
          <div class="st-cards">
            <div class="st-card"><h4>Category is abstract</h4><p>Sell concrete use cases first: board prep, product launch, sales positioning, research-to-action, AI strategy.</p></div>
            <div class="st-card"><h4>Product is too broad</h4><p>Lead with the core loop — Capture → Resolve → Frame → Measure → Remember — and a specific workspace as the entry point.</p></div>
            <div class="st-card"><h4>Machine layer ahead of readiness</h4><p>Sell Orient for Humans first; introduce machine access where customers already have agents or clear plans.</p></div>
            <div class="st-card"><h4>Compared to KB / RAG</h4><p>Use the sharp contrast — RAG gives chunks, Orient gives meaning — and show answers, evidence, contradictions, probes, and safe-to-act signals.</p></div>
            <div class="st-card"><h4>Long enterprise cycles</h4><p>Start with founder-led design partners and team-level deployments. Land with a strategic project, not an enterprise-wide rollout.</p></div>
            <div class="st-card"><h4>Meaning quality must be high</h4><p>Make human review central. Machines may propose meaning; humans confirm it.</p></div>
            <div class="st-card"><h4>Writeback could poison the graph</h4><p>Start read-only. Add guarded writeback later with review, provenance, confidence discounting, and audit.</p></div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 19 -->
        <section id="investor">
          <span class="sec-eyebrow">19 · Investor narrative</span>
          <h2>The agent era creates a new infrastructure need.</h2>
          <p>As agents move from chat to action, they need organisational meaning before they act. Today companies try to solve this with retrieval, document search, and disconnected copilots — and that is not enough. Agents need to know what the organisation currently believes, what supports it, what is contested, what's decided, what's stale, what's understood, and when not to act.</p>
          <p>Orient creates that missing layer. The human product is the wedge: teams think, resolve, frame, communicate, and remember. The machine product is the expansion: agents, assistants, workflows, copilots, and applications consume the meaning graph created by human work.</p>
          <p>This gives Orient a differentiated commercial model: seats for humans; dependency pricing for machines; expansion from team workspace to organisational infrastructure.</p>
          <div class="st-line m">Orient is not selling another tool. It is selling the layer beneath future human-machine work.</div>
        </section>

